Looking at the provided code fragments, I can see that the `hexi::endian` namespace provides a `conditional_reverse` function that handles endianness conversion. Based on this, here's the complete implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/endian.h>
#include <cstdint>
#include <bit>

template<typename T>
T convert_to_big_endian(T value) {
    return hexi::endian::conditional_reverse(value, std::endian::native, std::endian::big);
}

template<typename T>
T convert_from_big_endian(T value) {
    return hexi::endian::conditional_reverse(value, std::endian::big, std::endian::native);
}

template<typename T>
T convert_to_little_endian(T value) {
    return hexi::endian::conditional_reverse(value, std::endian::native, std::endian::little);
}

template<typename T>
T convert_from_little_endian(T value) {
    return hexi::endian::conditional_reverse(value, std::endian::little, std::endian::native);
}
```

The implementation uses the `hexi::endian::conditional_reverse` function which:
- Takes the value to convert, the source endianness, and the target endianness
- Automatically handles different types (integers, floats, doubles) using appropriate byte swapping
- Only performs the conversion if the source and target endianness differ
- Uses `std::byteswap` for integers and bit casting for floating-point types

The `<bit>` header is included for `std::endian` which provides the endianness constants.

