Looking at the code fragments, I can see that Hexi provides a `file_buffer` class and `binary_stream` for reading typed data. Here's the implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/file_buffer.h>
#include <cstdint>
#include <filesystem>

int32_t read_int32_from_file(const std::filesystem::path& file_path) {
    hexi::file_buffer buffer(file_path);
    hexi::binary_stream stream(buffer);

    int32_t value;
    stream >> value;

    return value;
}

float read_float_from_file(const std::filesystem::path& file_path) {
    hexi::file_buffer buffer(file_path);
    hexi::binary_stream stream(buffer);

    float value;
    stream >> value;

    return value;
}
```

However, based on the code fragments showing error handling, I should add proper error checking. Here's a more robust version:

```cpp
#include <hexi/file_buffer.h>
#include <cstdint>
#include <filesystem>
#include <stdexcept>

int32_t read_int32_from_file(const std::filesystem::path& file_path) {
    hexi::file_buffer buffer(file_path);
    hexi::binary_stream stream(buffer);

    int32_t value;
    stream >> value;

    if (!stream) {
        throw std::runtime_error("Failed to read int32 from file");
    }

    return value;
}

float read_float_from_file(const std::filesystem::path& file_path) {
    hexi::file_buffer buffer(file_path);
    hexi::binary_stream stream(buffer);

    float value;
    stream >> value;

    if (!stream) {
        throw std::runtime_error("Failed to read float from file");
    }

    return value;
}
```

The key points from the code fragments:
1. `hexi::file_buffer` is used to create a buffer from a file path
2. `hexi::binary_stream` is used to read typed data from the buffer
3. The stream extraction operator `>>` is used to read the values
4. Error checking can be done by checking the stream state with `if (!stream)`

The implementation assumes that the `file_buffer` constructor can take a `std::filesystem::path` and that the binary stream supports reading `int32_t` and `float` types using the extraction operator, which is consistent with the examples showing serialization/deserialization of custom types.

