Looking at the Hexi library usage patterns from the code fragments, I can implement the string read/write functions using the prefixed format. Here's the complete implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/pmc/binary_stream_writer.h>
#include <hexi/pmc/binary_stream_reader.h>
#include <hexi/pmc/buffer_adaptor.h>
#include <string>

void write_string_to_stream(hexi::pmc::binary_stream_writer& writer, const std::string& str) {
    // Write the length of the string as a prefix
    writer.write_varint(static_cast<uint32_t>(str.length()));

    // Write the string data
    if (!str.empty()) {
        writer.write(str.data(), str.length());
    }
}

std::string read_string_from_stream(hexi::pmc::binary_stream_reader& reader) {
    // Read the length prefix
    uint32_t length = reader.read_varint();

    // Read the string data
    std::string result;
    if (length > 0) {
        result.resize(length);
        reader.read(result.data(), length);
    }

    return result;
}
```

This implementation follows the common pattern seen in the Hexi library examples:

1. **Writing**: First writes the string length as a varint (variable-length integer) prefix, then writes the actual string data.
2. **Reading**: First reads the length prefix, then reads that many bytes into a string.

The varint format is efficient for storing small integers and is commonly used in binary serialization formats. The implementation handles empty strings correctly and uses the standard Hexi library methods `write_varint()`, `read_varint()`, `write()`, and `read()`.

