#include <hexi/pmc/buffer_adaptor.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>

void write_container_to_stream(hexi::pmc::binary_stream_writer& writer, const std::vector<uint32_t>& container) {
    // Write the count of elements first
    writer.write(static_cast<uint32_t>(container.size()));

    // Write each element in the container
    for (const auto& element : container) {
        writer.write(element);
    }
}

std::vector<uint32_t> read_container_from_stream(hexi::pmc::binary_stream_reader& reader) {
    std::vector<uint32_t> container;

    // Read the count of elements first
    uint32_t count;
    reader.read(count);

    // Reserve space for efficiency
    container.reserve(count);

    // Read each element
    for (uint32_t i = 0; i < count; ++i) {
        uint32_t element;
        reader.read(element);
        container.push_back(element);
    }

    return container;
}
```

Key points about this implementation:

1. **Writing**: First writes the count of elements as a `uint32_t`, then writes each element individually using the `write()` method of `binary_stream_writer`.

2. **Reading**: First reads the count, reserves space in the vector for efficiency, then reads each element individually using the `read()` method of `binary_stream_reader`.

3. **Type Safety**: Uses `uint32_t` consistently for both the count and elements, matching the function signatures.

4. **Efficiency**: Uses `reserve()` to pre-allocate the vector space, avoiding multiple reallocations when reading large containers.

The implementation follows the typical pattern shown in the Hexi library examples where streams are used to read/write fundamental data types sequentially.

