Looking at the code fragments, I can see that the `buffer_adaptor` has a `copy()` method that copies data without advancing the read pointer. Here's the implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/pmc/buffer_adaptor.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>
#include <cstring>

void peek_data_from_buffer(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer, void* data, std::size_t length) {
    // Use the copy method to copy data without advancing read pointer
    buffer.copy(data, length);
}

template<typename T>
void peek_value_from_buffer(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer, T& value) {
    // Use the template version of copy for single values
    buffer.copy(value);
}

bool peek_and_compare(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer, const void* expected, std::size_t length) {
    // Create a temporary buffer to peek the data
    std::vector<std::byte> temp(length);

    // Peek the data from the buffer
    buffer.copy(temp.data(), length);

    // Compare with expected data
    return std::memcmp(temp.data(), expected, length) == 0;
}
```

The implementation uses:

1. **`peek_data_from_buffer`**: Directly calls `buffer.copy(data, length)` which copies the specified number of bytes without advancing the read pointer.

2. **`peek_value_from_buffer`**: Uses the template version of `copy()` to copy a single value of type `T` without advancing the read pointer.

3. **`peek_and_compare`**: Creates a temporary buffer, peeks the data into it using `copy()`, then compares it with the expected data using `memcmp()`.

The `copy()` method is designed specifically for peeking operations as it doesn't modify the read position, unlike the `read()` method which would advance the pointer.

